name: Manmohan Singh
summary: Former Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, who served from 2004 to 2014, has passed away at the age of 92. Singh, known as India's "reluctant prime minister," oversaw a period of significant economic growth and reforms. During his tenure, he played a key role in implementing market-oriented policies that transformed India's economy. Singh's legacy is complex, with many praising his contributions to India's development while others criticizing his handling of certain issues. His passing has been met with tributes from political leaders, industry titans, and the international community, who recognize his significant impact on India's trajectory.

name: Todd McLellan
summary: The Detroit Red Wings have parted ways with head coach Derek Lalonde and have appointed Todd McLellan as his replacement. Lalonde's dismissal comes after a disappointing season in which the Red Wings finished last in the NHL standings. McLellan, a veteran coach with over a decade of NHL experience, will be tasked with rebuilding the team and improving its performance. This is his fourth NHL team as head coach, having previously led the Edmonton Oilers, San Jose Sharks, and Los Angeles Kings.

name: Geno Smith
summary: Geno Smith, quarterback for the Seattle Seahawks, has been dealing with a persistent knee injury and two interceptions in the recent "Big Game" against the Bears. Despite the setbacks, Smith remains focused on upcoming matches and downplays the impact of past performances. Smith is expected to play in the upcoming game against the Vikings. However, his knee injury is expected to linger. Financial details about Smith's net worth and annual salary have been reported, and analyst Mark Schlereth has weighed in on his future with the Seahawks. The team's defense received a boost with Dallas Turner securing his first career NFL interception in the game against the Vikings.

name: Jim Larranaga
summary: University of Miami's longtime head men's basketball coach, Jim Larrañaga, has announced his resignation amid a challenging season start. Larrañaga, the university's all-time winningest coach, cited exhaustion and the demanding business aspects of the sport as reasons for his departure. Assistant coach Bill Courtney will take over as interim head coach for the remainder of the season. Larrañaga's resignation comes two years after he led the Hurricanes to the Final Four.
